The P Hydro model with sperry optimization

Victor Flo

2022-08-01

The ProfitMax stomatal scheme (Sperry et al. 2016) is obtimised as: \[ F_{ProfitMax} = \frac{A_j}{A_{max}} - (\frac{k_\mathrm{\psi_s}-k_\mathrm{\psi_l}}{k_\mathrm{\psi_s}-k_\mathrm{\psi_{crit}}}) \] The profit maximization can be rewritten as: \[ F_{ProfitMax} = A_j - A_{max} (\frac{k_\mathrm{\psi_s}-k_\mathrm{\psi_l}}{k_\mathrm{\psi_s}-k_\mathrm{\psi_{crit}}}) \] Then we can easily account for photosynthetic cost: \[ F = A_j - A_{max} (\frac{k_\mathrm{\psi_s}-k_\mathrm{\psi_l}}{k_\mathrm{\psi_s}-k_\mathrm{\psi_{crit}}}) - \alpha J_\mathrm{max} \]

Red line represents the profit optimization function of the original ProfitMax scheme. In yellow the proposed profit function. The upper blue line is the relative assimilation component and the lower is the normalized hydraulic penalization. The dashed vertical line represents the dpsi where the maximum profit is obtained.

The components of the profit maximization function can be rewritten as: \[ A_j = g_\mathrm{s} c_\mathrm{a} (1-\chi) \]

\[ k_\mathrm{\psi_s} = K_{max}\;(\frac{1}{2})^{(\frac{\psi_s}{\psi_{50}})^b} \]

\[ k_\mathrm{\psi_l} = K_{max}\;(\frac{1}{2})^{(\frac{\psi_l}{\psi_{50}})^b} = K_{max}\;(\frac{1}{2})^{(\frac{\Delta\psi + |\psi_s|}{|\psi_{50}|})^b} \]

\[ k_\mathrm{\psi_{crit}} = K_{max}\;(\frac{1}{2})^{(\frac{\psi_{crit}}{\psi_{50}})^b} \]

Where \(\psi_{crit}\) is the critical leaf water potential as the potential at which 99.9% of conductivity loss would occur.

\[ P(\psi) = \frac{1}{2} ^{(\frac{\psi}{\psi_{50}})^b} \]

\[ if\; P(\psi) = 0.001 \; then: \; \psi_{crit} = \psi_{50}(\frac{ln(1000)}{ln(2)} )^{(\frac{1}{b})} \]

Which gives us the next expression that can be solved similarly as in the P Hydro analytical approximation, where each term is a function of the two independent variables \(\chi\) and \(\Delta \psi\). \[ F = g_\mathrm{s} c_\mathrm{a} (1-\chi)- A_{max} (\frac{k_\mathrm{\psi_s}- K_{max}\;(\frac{1}{2})^{(\frac{\Delta\psi + |\psi_s|}{|\psi_{50}|})^b}}{k_\mathrm{\psi_s}-k_\mathrm{\psi_{crit}}}) - \alpha J_\mathrm{max} \]

or: \[ F = g_\mathrm{s} c_\mathrm{a} (1-\chi) (k_\mathrm{\psi_s}-k_\mathrm{\psi_{crit}})- A_{max} (k_\mathrm{\psi_s}- K_{max}\;(\frac{1}{2})^{(\frac{\Delta\psi + |\psi_s|}{|\psi_{50}|})^b}) - \alpha J_\mathrm{max} (k_\mathrm{\psi_s}-k_\mathrm{\psi_{crit}}) \]

Solved by \(\chi\) \[ \frac{\partial F}{\partial \chi} = -g_s c_a(k_\mathrm{\psi_s}-k_\mathrm{\psi_{crit}}) -\alpha \frac{\partial J_\mathrm{max}}{\partial A_{Jm}} \frac{\partial A_{Jm}}{\partial \chi}( k_\mathrm{\psi_s}-k_\mathrm{\psi_{crit}}) = 0 \]

Solved by \(\Delta\psi\) \[ \frac{\partial F}{\partial \Delta\psi} = \frac{\partial g_s}{\partial \Delta\psi} c_a (1-\chi) (k_\mathrm{\psi_s}-k_\mathrm{\psi_{crit}})- \frac{A_{max}\;K_{max}\;ln(2)\;(\frac{\Delta\psi + |\psi_s|}{|\psi_{50}|})^b}{2\;(\Delta\psi + |\psi_s|)(\frac{\Delta\psi + |\psi_s|}{|\psi_{50}|})^b}- \alpha \frac{\partial J_\mathrm{max}}{\partial A_{Jm}} \frac{\partial A_{Jm}}{\partial \Delta\psi}(k_\mathrm{\psi_s}-k_\mathrm{\psi_{crit}})= 0 \]

Here I show surfaces obtained from the optimization function numerically at four different \(\psi_{s}\), a) -0.01, b) -1, c) -2 and d) -3 MPa (VPD = 1kPa). In this case the critical leaf potential is -4.9149669 MPa.

Now the same soil water potentials but expressed as Canopy conductance (gs)

Here I show the simulations for the soil potential gradient. The plant have a \(\psi_{50}\) = -3.46 a slope parameter of 6.55 and a \(K\) of 3e-17

One can see that there are some problems with the optimization close to \(\psi_{crit}\). \(\Delta\psi\) is optimised at the maximum possible value (\(\psi_s-\psi_{crit}\)) and \(J_{max}\) = is \(J_{max}(\psi_{s0})\). Any idea?
